const e=["Bone is composed of 70% inorganic (hydroxyapatite), 25% organic (Type I collagen), and 5% water","Osteoblasts form bone; osteoclasts resorb bone; osteocytes maintain bone","Haversian system (osteon) is the structural unit of compact bone","Volkmann's canals connect Haversian canals horizontally","Intramembranous ossification: flat bones (skull vault, maxilla, mandible body, clavicle)","Endochondral ossification: long bones and skull base","Mandible develops by both intramembranous (body) and endochondral (condyle) ossification","Pterion is the thinnest part of skull — fracture tears middle meningeal artery → epidural hematoma","Le Fort I: horizontal maxillary fracture (floating palate); Le Fort II: pyramidal; Le Fort III: craniofacial disjunction","Condylar fracture is the most common mandibular fracture","Angle of mandible fracture is common due to 3rd molar weakening the bone","Blow-out fracture of orbit: floor fracture → infraorbital nerve damage → numbness of cheek/upper lip","Zygomatic (tripod) fracture involves 3 sutures: frontozygomatic, zygomaticomaxillary, zygomaticotemporal","Battle's sign (mastoid bruising) indicates base of skull fracture","CSF rhinorrhea/otorrhea with halo sign indicates base of skull fracture"],a="\n# OSTEOLOGY & FRACTURES — HIGH-YIELD SUMMARY\n\n**Exam Scope:** Osteology and fractures are repeatedly tested in FCPS Part 1. Focus on bone classification, ossification types, skull foramina with structures passing through, and clinical fracture patterns (especially Le Fort classification and mandibular fractures).\n\n**References:** Snell's Clinical Anatomy, BD Chaurasia, Gray's Anatomy for Students\n\n---\n\n## 1. BONE — BASIC CONCEPTS\n\n### Composition of Bone\n| Component | Percentage | Details |\n|-----------|-----------|---------|\n| Inorganic | ~70% | Hydroxyapatite crystals (calcium phosphate) — gives **hardness** |\n| Organic | ~25% | Type I collagen fibers — gives **tensile strength & flexibility** |\n| Water | ~5% | — |\n\n### Bone Cells\n\n| Cell | Function | Origin | Key Marker |\n|------|----------|--------|------------|\n| **Osteoblasts** | Bone formation (lay down osteoid) | Mesenchyme | Alkaline phosphatase (ALP) |\n| **Osteocytes** | Maintenance, mechanosensing | Trapped osteoblasts | In lacunae, connected by canaliculi |\n| **Osteoclasts** | Bone resorption | Monocyte-macrophage lineage (hematopoietic) | TRAP (tartrate-resistant acid phosphatase), ruffled border, Howship's lacunae |\n\n> **High-yield:** Osteoclasts are the ONLY bone cells derived from **hematopoietic** (monocyte) lineage. Osteoblasts and osteocytes come from **mesenchyme**.\n\n### Classification of Bones\n\n| Type | Examples |\n|------|----------|\n| Long bones | Humerus, femur, radius, ulna, metacarpals, phalanges |\n| Short bones | Carpals, tarsals |\n| Flat bones | Skull vault, sternum, scapula, ribs |\n| Irregular bones | Vertebrae, sphenoid, ethmoid, mandible |\n| Sesamoid bones | Patella, pisiform |\n| Pneumatic bones | Maxilla, frontal, sphenoid, ethmoid (contain air sinuses) |\n\n---\n\n## 2. STRUCTURE OF BONE\n\n### Compact (Cortical) Bone\n- Forms the outer shell (cortex) of all bones\n- Structural unit = **Haversian system (osteon)**\n  - Central **Haversian canal** — contains blood vessels and nerves\n  - Concentric **lamellae** — layers of bone matrix around the canal\n  - **Lacunae** — spaces housing osteocytes\n  - **Canaliculi** — tiny channels connecting lacunae (cell communication)\n- **Volkmann's canals** — horizontal/oblique canals connecting adjacent Haversian canals and periosteum\n\n### Cancellous (Spongy/Trabecular) Bone\n- Found inside bones (epiphyses of long bones, interior of flat/irregular bones)\n- Network of **trabeculae** — oriented along lines of stress\n- Spaces filled with **bone marrow** (red in active sites, yellow in adults)\n\n### Periosteum\n- Outer fibrous layer: attachment for tendons/ligaments\n- Inner osteogenic (cambium) layer: contains osteoprogenitor cells — responsible for **appositional growth** and fracture repair\n- Absent at articular surfaces (replaced by hyaline cartilage)\n- **Sharpey's fibers** anchor periosteum to bone\n\n### Endosteum\n- Thin connective tissue lining medullary cavity\n- Contains osteoprogenitor cells\n- Active in bone remodeling\n\n---\n\n## 3. OSSIFICATION\n\n### Intramembranous Ossification\n- Bone forms **directly from mesenchyme** (no cartilage model)\n- Mesenchymal cells → osteoblasts → secrete osteoid → mineralization\n- **Bones formed:**\n  - Skull vault (frontal, parietal, parts of occipital, temporal)\n  - Maxilla\n  - Body of mandible\n  - Clavicle (only long bone by intramembranous ossification)\n  - Part of facial skeleton\n\n### Endochondral Ossification\n- Bone replaces a **hyaline cartilage model**\n- Steps:\n  1. Cartilage model forms\n  2. Perichondrium becomes periosteum → periosteal bone collar\n  3. Primary ossification center appears in diaphysis (center of shaft)\n  4. Secondary ossification centers appear in epiphyses (after birth)\n  5. Growth plate (epiphyseal plate/physis) between diaphysis and epiphysis\n- **Bones formed:**\n  - Long bones (limbs)\n  - Base of skull (occipital base, sphenoid body, petrous temporal)\n  - Vertebrae\n  - Condyle of mandible\n\n> **Mandible** — unique: body by **intramembranous**, condyle by **endochondral** ossification.\n\n### Zones of Growth Plate (Epiphyseal Plate)\nFrom epiphysis → diaphysis:\n\n| Zone | Activity |\n|------|----------|\n| **Reserve (resting)** | Stores nutrients, anchors plate to epiphysis |\n| **Proliferation** | Active cell division — chondrocytes stack in columns |\n| **Hypertrophy** | Chondrocytes enlarge, mature |\n| **Calcification** | Cartilage matrix calcifies, chondrocytes die |\n| **Ossification** | Osteoblasts lay down bone on calcified cartilage scaffolding |\n\n> Growth plate closes under the influence of **estrogen** (in both males and females). This is why precocious puberty → short stature.\n\n---\n\n## 4. SKULL OSTEOLOGY — HIGH-YIELD POINTS\n\n### Skull Bones\n- **Calvaria (vault):** Frontal, 2 Parietal, Occipital (superior part), 2 Temporal (squamous part)\n- **Base:** Sphenoid, Ethmoid, Occipital (basilar part), Temporal (petrous part)\n- **Facial:** Maxilla, Mandible, Zygomatic, Nasal, Lacrimal, Palatine, Vomer, Inferior nasal concha\n\n### Important Skull Landmarks\n\n| Landmark | Clinical Significance |\n|----------|----------------------|\n| **Pterion** | Thinnest skull area; overlies middle meningeal artery; fracture → **epidural hematoma** |\n| **Asterion** | Junction of occipital, temporal, parietal; overlies transverse-sigmoid sinus junction |\n| **Bregma** | Anterior fontanelle (junction of coronal + sagittal sutures); closes at **18 months** |\n| **Lambda** | Posterior fontanelle (junction of sagittal + lambdoid sutures); closes at **2–3 months** |\n| **Nasion** | Junction of frontal and 2 nasal bones |\n| **Inion** | External occipital protuberance |\n| **Glabella** | Smooth area between superciliary arches |\n\n### Key Foramina & Structures\n\n| Foramen | Structures Passing Through |\n|---------|---------------------------|\n| **Foramen ovale** | Mandibular nerve (V3), accessory meningeal artery, lesser petrosal nerve |\n| **Foramen rotundum** | Maxillary nerve (V2) |\n| **Foramen spinosum** | Middle meningeal artery, meningeal branch of V3 |\n| **Superior orbital fissure** | CN III, IV, V1 (ophthalmic), VI, ophthalmic veins |\n| **Inferior orbital fissure** | Maxillary nerve (V2), infraorbital vessels |\n| **Foramen magnum** | Medulla oblongata, vertebral arteries, spinal accessory nerve (CN XI) |\n| **Jugular foramen** | CN IX, X, XI; internal jugular vein |\n| **Internal acoustic meatus** | CN VII (facial), CN VIII (vestibulocochlear), labyrinthine artery |\n| **Hypoglossal canal** | CN XII (hypoglossal nerve) |\n| **Stylomastoid foramen** | CN VII (exit after traversing temporal bone) |\n| **Carotid canal** | Internal carotid artery |\n| **Foramen lacerum** | Internal carotid artery passes over it (NOT through it); deep petrosal nerve |\n| **Cribriform plate** | Olfactory nerve fibers (CN I) |\n| **Optic canal** | CN II (optic nerve), ophthalmic artery |\n\n> **Mnemonic for Jugular foramen:** \"Glossy Vagus Accessory\" → CN IX, X, XI\n\n### Cranial Fossae\n\n| Fossa | Bones | Key Contents |\n|-------|-------|-------------|\n| **Anterior** | Frontal, ethmoid (cribriform plate), lesser wing of sphenoid | Frontal lobe, olfactory bulbs |\n| **Middle** | Greater wing of sphenoid, temporal (squamous & petrous) | Temporal lobe, pituitary (sella turcica), middle meningeal artery |\n| **Posterior** | Occipital, petrous temporal | Cerebellum, brainstem, foramen magnum |\n\n---\n\n## 5. MANDIBLE — DETAILED ANATOMY\n\n### Parts\n- **Body:** Horizontal, horseshoe-shaped; bears alveolar process superiorly\n- **Ramus:** Vertical part; has coronoid process (anterior) and condylar process (posterior) separated by mandibular notch\n- **Angle:** Where body meets ramus (~110–120°)\n- **Mental foramen:** Below 2nd premolar — exits mental nerve (branch of V3)\n- **Mandibular foramen:** Medial surface of ramus — entry of inferior alveolar nerve (V3)\n- **Lingula:** Bony projection near mandibular foramen — landmark for inferior alveolar nerve block\n\n### Muscles of Mastication (all supplied by V3)\n| Muscle | Action | Attachment |\n|--------|--------|------------|\n| **Masseter** | Elevation (strongest bite) | Zygomatic arch → angle of mandible |\n| **Temporalis** | Elevation & retraction | Temporal fossa → coronoid process |\n| **Medial pterygoid** | Elevation & side-to-side | Pterygoid fossa → medial surface of angle |\n| **Lateral pterygoid** | Depression, protrusion, side-to-side | Greater wing of sphenoid → TMJ disc & condyle |\n\n> **Only muscle that opens the jaw:** Lateral pterygoid (inferior head) + suprahyoid muscles (digastric, geniohyoid, mylohyoid)\n\n---\n\n## 6. FRACTURES — CLINICAL HIGH-YIELD\n\n### Le Fort Classification (Maxillary Fractures)\n\n| Type | Pattern | Clinical Name | Key Feature |\n|------|---------|---------------|-------------|\n| **Le Fort I** | Horizontal fracture above alveolar process | **Floating palate** | Palate moves independently; separates maxillary alveolus from upper face |\n| **Le Fort II** | Pyramidal fracture through nasion, lacrimal, orbital floor, zygomatic buttress | **Floating maxilla** | Nose & maxilla move together; infraorbital numbness, CSF leak possible |\n| **Le Fort III** | Complete craniofacial separation through nasofrontal, orbital walls, zygomatic arches | **Craniofacial disjunction** | Entire midface moves independently from skull; \"dish face\" |\n\n> **All Le Fort fractures** pass through the **pterygoid plates** of the sphenoid bone.\n\n### Mandibular Fractures\n\n| Site | Frequency | Clinical Notes |\n|------|-----------|---------------|\n| **Condyle** | Most common (~35%) | Restricted mouth opening, deviation to affected side, malocclusion |\n| **Angle** | ~20% | Weakened by unerupted 3rd molar; favorable/unfavorable depending on muscle pull |\n| **Body** | ~20% | Often bilateral (parasymphysis); mental nerve may be damaged |\n| **Symphysis/Parasymphysis** | ~15% | Airway compromise risk (bilateral → tongue falls back) |\n\n> **Favorable vs. Unfavorable fracture:** Depends on whether the fracture line resists or aids displacement by muscle pull. Unfavorable fractures are displaced by muscles of mastication.\n\n### Zygomatic (Tripod/Trimalar) Fracture\n- Fracture through **3 suture lines:**\n  1. Frontozygomatic suture\n  2. Zygomaticomaxillary suture\n  3. Zygomaticotemporal suture\n- Clinical: **Flattened cheek**, periorbital ecchymosis, trismus, infraorbital numbness (V2)\n- May involve orbital floor → diplopia\n\n### Blow-Out Fracture (Orbital Floor)\n- Caused by blunt trauma to the orbit (e.g., ball, fist)\n- Orbital contents herniate into maxillary sinus\n- **Inferior rectus muscle** may get trapped → restricted upward gaze (diplopia)\n- **Infraorbital nerve** damage → numbness of cheek, upper lip, upper teeth\n- Enophthalmos (sunken eye) if severe\n\n### Base of Skull Fracture\n- **Anterior cranial fossa fracture:**\n  - Raccoon eyes (bilateral periorbital ecchymosis)\n  - CSF rhinorrhea (CSF leak from nose via cribriform plate fracture)\n  - Anosmia (CN I damage)\n- **Middle cranial fossa fracture:**\n  - CSF otorrhea (CSF from ear)\n  - Battle's sign (bruising behind ear — mastoid ecchymosis)\n  - CN VII and VIII may be damaged (facial palsy, hearing loss)\n- **Halo test:** CSF mixed with blood forms double ring on gauze/linen (blood in center, clear CSF halo around it)\n\n### Nasal Bone Fracture\n- **Most commonly fractured facial bone**\n- Diagnosis: clinical examination + lateral X-ray\n- Complications: septal hematoma → if not drained → abscess → **saddle nose deformity**\n\n---\n\n## 7. FRACTURE HEALING\n\n### Stages\n1. **Hematoma formation** (0–5 days): Blood clot at fracture site\n2. **Inflammatory phase** (1–7 days): Macrophages clear debris; granulation tissue forms\n3. **Soft callus** (2–3 weeks): Fibrocartilaginous callus bridges the gap\n4. **Hard callus** (3–12 weeks): Woven bone replaces soft callus (endochondral ossification)\n5. **Remodeling** (months–years): Woven bone → lamellar bone; Wolff's law applies\n\n> **Wolff's Law:** Bone remodels along lines of mechanical stress — trabeculae orient to resist applied forces.\n\n### Factors Affecting Healing\n| Promotes Healing | Delays Healing |\n|------------------|----------------|\n| Good blood supply | Infection |\n| Adequate immobilization | Movement at fracture site |\n| Youth | Old age, malnutrition |\n| Growth hormone, thyroid hormones | Corticosteroids, NSAIDs |\n| Vitamin D, Calcium | Vitamin C deficiency (scurvy) |\n\n---\n\n## 8. METABOLIC BONE DISEASES (Quick Reference)\n\n| Disease | Pathology | Key Features |\n|---------|-----------|--------------|\n| **Osteoporosis** | Decreased bone mass, normal mineralization | Post-menopausal, compression fractures, DEXA scan |\n| **Osteomalacia / Rickets** | Defective mineralization (Vitamin D deficiency) | Rickets in children (bowed legs, craniotabes, rachitic rosary); osteomalacia in adults |\n| **Paget's Disease** | Excessive disorganized remodeling | Elevated ALP, hearing loss, lion-like facies (leontiasis ossea), mosaic pattern on histology |\n| **Osteogenesis Imperfecta** | Type I collagen defect | Blue sclera, multiple fractures, \"brittle bone disease\" |\n| **Osteopetrosis** | Defective osteoclast function | Dense but brittle bones (\"marble bone disease\"), pancytopenia |\n\n> **Osteoporosis:** Normal Ca²⁺, normal PO₄, normal ALP\n> **Osteomalacia:** Low Ca²⁺, low PO₄, HIGH ALP\n> **Paget's:** Normal Ca²⁺, normal PO₄, VERY HIGH ALP\n";export{e as O,a};
